A new study shows that minorities are given far less opportunity than their white peers, are taught by less experienced teachers, and made up the majority of students arrested.

According to the U.S. Department of Education’s Office for Civil Rights, black students – especially males - are three and a half times as likely to be suspended or expelled, according to the report.

More than 70 per cent of students involved in school-related arrests or cases referred to law enforcement were Hispanic or African-American.

